that one for a detailed explanation on Orwell’s thoughts about how to write.

00:21:23.353 --> 00:21:23.977
Let's start with a couple of examples.

00:21:26.879 --> 00:21:32.849
The most important point for me is about how one should always use simple language, when possible.

00:21:33.749 --> 00:21:39.079
Orwell says “Political language…..is designed to make lies sound truthful

00:21:39.419 --> 00:21:45.969
and murder respectable, and to give an appearance of solidity to pure wind.”

00:21:46.759 --> 00:21:52.049
He hated seeing people use overly complicated language as a way of twisting

00:21:52.169 --> 00:21:57.469
a message, and was always a great supporter of simple, clear, simple words.

00:21:58.109 --> 00:22:03.299
I’m always reminded of Orwell whenever I see terrible videos on social

00:22:03.299 --> 00:22:08.089
media, on Instagram and things, of English teachers saying things like

00:22:08.259 --> 00:22:14.139
“Don’t say go up, say elevate”, or "don't say people, say inhabitants".

00:22:14.399 --> 00:22:19.959
It’s just complete rubbish, if you follow this sort of advice you’ll end up talking

00:22:19.959 --> 00:22:25.699
like a robotic dictionary, and Orwell would be turning in his grave if he could see it.

00:22:26.199 --> 00:22:27.409
So, don’t do it.

00:22:28.329 --> 00:22:34.649
Finally, I’ll leave you with three curiosities about the great man, three weird facts.

00:22:35.199 --> 00:22:39.729
Firstly, as you may know, George Orwell wasn’t his real name.

00:22:40.019 --> 00:22:43.029
He was born with the name Eric Blair.

00:22:43.709 --> 00:22:45.559
George Orwell was his pen name.

00:22:46.059 --> 00:22:48.959
He took inspiration from the name of the king for the first

00:22:49.169 --> 00:22:52.773
name and from the name of a local river for his second.

00:22:53.619 --> 00:22:57.979
Secondly, the script of Animal Farm was very nearly

00:22:57.989 --> 00:23:02.459
lost when Orwell‘s house was destroyed by a German bomb.

00:23:02.939 --> 00:23:06.599
The anxious author had to dig in the rubble, to dig

00:23:06.699 --> 00:23:09.729
through the fallen bricks, in order to retrieve it.

00:23:10.559 --> 00:23:16.849
And finally, as Orwell approached death with tuberculosis he asked three different

00:23:16.859 --> 00:23:22.359
young women to marry him, wanting companionship and saying that they had an excellent

00:23:22.389 --> 00:23:27.969
chance of shortly becoming rich widows on the proceeds of his highly successful books.

00:23:28.799 --> 00:23:31.455
The third one, Sonia Bronwell, accepted him.

00:23:32.085 --> 00:23:35.945
He is said to have worn a lilac-coloured smoking jacket as

00:23:35.945 --> 00:23:38.975
he lay in the bed where he would die three months later.

00:23:39.835 --> 00:23:44.605
Orwell was a man of huge talent, and who knows what

00:23:44.615 --> 00:23:47.325
he might have given us had he lived a longer life.

00:23:47.914 --> 00:23:54.044
His writing is timeless, it is as appropriate now as it was in 1948, and I’m

00:23:54.044 --> 00:23:57.794
sure that people will still be talking about Orwell in hundreds of years time.

00:23:58.304 --> 00:24:03.624
Like any great writer, the themes that Orwell chooses are universal.

00:24:04.264 --> 00:24:08.174
We learn through universal human truths, through ideas

00:24:08.284 --> 00:24:11.334
and subjects that every single person can relate to.

00:24:11.814 --> 00:24:18.144
Joy, food, love, desire, humour, language, and of course, animals.

00:24:18.844 --> 00:24:22.884
I’ll just leave you with one of my favourite thought-provoking quotes from

00:24:22.894 --> 00:24:27.174
Nineteen Eighty Four, which comes from the evil character, Big Brother.

00:24:28.224 --> 00:24:32.404
And that’s “Who controls the past controls the future.

00:24:33.274 --> 00:24:36.444
Who controls the present controls the past.”

